instruction:
If \begin{equation*}
  A =
  \begin{bmatrix}
    1 & 2 \\
    3 & 5 \\
  \end{bmatrix},
\end{equation*}
find the inverse of A using the method of elementary row operations.

output:
To find the inverse of matrix A using elementary row operations, we will augment matrix A with the identity matrix and perform row operations until the left side becomes the identity matrix. The right side will then be the inverse of A.

Step 1: Augment matrix A with the identity matrix

\begin{equation*}
  \begin{bmatrix}
    1 & 2 & | & 1 & 0 \\
    3 & 5 & | & 0 & 1 \\
  \end{bmatrix}
\end{equation*}

Step 2: Perform row operations to get a 1 in the top left corner (if not already there)

In this case, we already have a 1 in the top left corner, so we can move on to the next step.

Step 3: Perform row operations to get a 0 below the 1 in the top left corner

Subtract 3 times the first row from the second row:

\begin{equation*}
  \begin{bmatrix}
    1 & 2 & | & 1 & 0 \\
    0 & -1 & | & -3 & 1 \\
  \end{bmatrix}
\end{equation*}

Step 4: Perform row operations to get a 1 in the second row and second column

Multiply the second row by -1:

\begin{equation*}
  \begin{bmatrix}
    1 & 2 & | & 1 & 0 \\
    0 & 1 & | & 3 & -1 \\
  \end{bmatrix}
\end{equation*}

Step 5: Perform row operations to get a 0 above the 1 in the second row and second column

Subtract 2 times the second row from the first row:

\begin{equation*}
  \begin{bmatrix}
    1 & 0 & | & -5 & 2 \\
    0 & 1 & | & 3 & -1 \\
  \end{bmatrix}
\end{equation*}

Now, the left side of the augmented matrix is the identity matrix, and the right side is the inverse of A:

\begin{equation*}
  A^{-1} =
  \begin{bmatrix}
    -5 & 2 \\
    3 & -1 \\
  \end{bmatrix}
\end{equation*}

import math

def count_divisors(n):
    # Initialize result
    count = 0
    i = 1
    while i <= math.sqrt(n):
        # if i is a factor of n
        if n % i == 0:
            # if both divisors are same then add one
            if n/i == i:
                if i % 3 == 0:
                    count += 1
            else:
                # else add 2
                if i % 3 == 0:
                    count += 1
                if (n/i) % 3 == 0:
                    count += 1
        i += 1
    return count

n = 3240
print(count_divisors(n))

